Correct! Never leave work devices unattended where a criminal can easily steal them, especially in a car. Plus, you wouldnt want to end your work day dealing with a break-in.
You are awesome, you got them all!! Close the popup to see the final screen.
Looks like someone didnt get enough coffee this morning.
Peek-a-boo!! Ratty is trying to creep his way inside.
Shhh, Ratty is incognito. No one can tell the difference.
Not quite. Although your co-workers may find out more information about you than they would like to, watching videos or skimming social media is not a security risk.
No slacking off, humans. Get back to work!
Correct! Have all sensitive conversations in private locations where eavesdropping is unlikely to happen. Everyone knows people like to gossip around the water cooler during break time.
Wait a minute!! Where is your hall pass?

Not quite. Outside parties should always check in with the front desk before entering the premises. The front desk takes its job of vetting suspicious people from entering the building very seriously and will make sure mischief makers are not allowed in.

Correct! A great rule of thumb: Never let a random person follow you into a building. You never know what kind of mischief they are planning to get into. All outside visitors need to check in with the front desk before entering the premises to make sure they are not a security risk.

Correct! Information written during a meeting should always be erased or collected once the meeting is over. It takes less than a minute for an unauthorized person to snap a picture of confidential information and use it to sabotage your organization.

Correct! Work should always be done in a location where others cannot easily see the information on your screen, especially if it is sensitive information. People are nosy; its just a matter of time before a criminal peeks over your shoulder and steals information.

Not quite. Confidential information is often shared with staff members throughout the day. As long as everything is erased from the whiteboards at the end of the meeting, this information is not at risk. Keep all meeting notes in a secure place.
Sorry, Ratty, the meeting was yesterday.

Not quite. Although not recommended, it is not a security risk for non-work-related devices to be stored in vehicles or around the office without supervision. Unfortunately, if you leave it in your car, you wont be able to play battle royale during your lunch.
Bigfoot, can we get a photo with you? Dont worry, we wont sell it to the tabloids.
Ratty is looking to score some files from the cabinet. Too bad everything is locked.
Ratty is working hard to get that promotion.

Correct! Devices should always be locked when not in use to prevent criminals from lurking and stealing important information. Even if you think your information is useless, you never know what can be used against you and your organization. It is always better to be safe than sorry.

Correct! Sensitive documents should always be locked away or with the person in charge. Leaving a filing cabinet drawer open is not only a tripping hazard, but its also a warm welcome for criminals to swoop in and steal information.
Run away, Ratty, before the janitor sees you!!

Correct! Back doors should be supervised to make sure unauthorized individuals cant access the building. Open doors could lead to a host of dangerous situations, including shady individuals sneaking in and stealing whatever they can find.
Its been a rough day of causing mischief for Ratty; time for a snack!

Correct! Never use a USB or external device that has not been preapproved by the IT department or management, as tempting as it may be. Criminals can use external devices once they are plugged in to hack into the network or install malware. Dont be the reason hackers find a way in.

Not quite. Public documents are not a security threat and can be accessed by employees and outsiders at any time. Anyone who tries to steal the information and sell it is in for a world of disappointment.

Correct! Never post passwords and other sensitive information around the office. Post-its are fantastic for many things, but storing passwords is not one of them. Also, someone may want to rethink that password. Having a password with 1234 in it is a surefire way to get hacked.
Oh no! Ratty needed just a few more minutes to hack into the network.
Not quite. Everyone needs to write notes once in a while. Unless you are worried about the people around you knowing what kind of milk you buy, grocery lists are safe to have on your desk.
Ratty is eager for a chat. If only someone would pay attention to him.
Awesome!! You found all of the mischievous rats! Now the staff can finally work in peace. Heres an extra life as thanks for rodent patrol.
Oh no! You ran out of lives. :( Better luck next time! Close the popup to see the final screen and try again.
We dont need roads where we are going.

The objective is simple: find and left click on all 10 security risks around the office and you win the game. Beware of the red herrings! If you click on something that is not an actual risk you may lose one of your lives. But dont worry, you can gain an extra life if you find all 10 rats.

Good luck and have fun!

[i][u]Left click[/u][/i] on different elements to see what youve found - a rat, security risk, a red herring, or something else.

Zoom in and out of the scene by using the [i][u]scroll wheel[/i][/u] or the on screen zoom buttons.

Move around the scene by [i][u]right clicking[/i][/u] and dragging with your mouse or using the on screen arrows.

How to Play

The objective is simple: find all 10 security risks around the office, and you win the game. Beware of the red herrings! If you click on something that is not an actual risk you may lose one of your lives. But dont worry, you can gain an extra life if you find all 10 rats.

  • You can use the Tab or Shift + Tab to move from hotspot to hotspot or to the on-screen controls. When you find a hotspot you think is a risky situation, hit enter.
  • If you need to zoom in or out, use your mouse scroll wheel or navigate to the on-screen controls.
  • You can also navigate to the on-screen controls or click and drag the right button on your mouse to explore the office.

Good luck and have fun!
